Thanks for the detailed report!

The root cause appears to be in `SKFont.ContainsGlyphs`. The heart emoji `❤️` is actually two UTF-16 characters: `❤` (U+2764) and the variation selector `️` (U+FE0F). When `ContainsGlyphs` calls `GetGlyphs` on the full string, it gets two glyph IDs. The variation selector U+FE0F doesn't have its own standalone glyph in most Android fonts, so it maps to glyph ID 0. Since `ContainsGlyphs` currently returns `false` if *any* glyph is 0, the whole check fails.

**Workaround:** Use the `ReadOnlySpan<int>` overload of `ContainsGlyphs` with individual Unicode codepoints, skipping variation selectors:

```csharp
// Enumerate text as Unicode scalar values, skip variation selectors
var codepoints = new List<int>();
foreach (var rune in text.EnumerateRunes())
{
    // Skip variation selectors (U+FE00–U+FE0F and U+E0100–U+E01EF)
    if (rune.Value is >= 0xFE00 and <= 0xFE0F)
        continue;
    codepoints.Add(rune.Value);
}
bool hasGlyphs = font.ContainsGlyphs(System.Runtime.InteropServices.MemoryMarshal.Cast<int, int>(codepoints.ToArray()));
```

Alternatively, use `SKTypeface.ContainsGlyphs(ReadOnlySpan<int> codepoints)` directly.

We'll investigate fixing `ContainsGlyphs` to handle variation selectors correctly.
